.TH HSH 1 "April 2026" "1.0" "Simple Shell Manual"
.SH NAME
hsh \- a simple UNIX command line interpreter
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ./hsh
.RI [ command \ [ arguments ... ]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hsh
is a simple UNIX command line interpreter written in C that reads commands
from standard input and executes them. It supports both interactive and
non-interactive modes.
In
.B interactive mode,
the shell displays a prompt
.B ($)
and waits for the user to enter a command.
In
.B non-interactive mode,
the shell reads commands from a pipe or file without displaying a prompt.
.SH USAGE
.TP
.B Interactive mode:
.nf
$ ./hsh
$ ls
AUTHORS  builtins.c  executor.c  hsh  main.c  parser.c  path.c  shell.h
$ exit
.fi
.TP
.B Non-interactive mode:
.nf
$ echo "ls" | ./hsh
AUTHORS  builtins.c  executor.c  hsh  main.c  parser.c  path.c  shell.h
.fi
.SH EXECUTION
When a command is entered, the shell performs the following steps:
.IP 1. 3
Reads a line of input using
.BR getline (3).
.IP 2. 3
Checks for EOF or empty line.
.IP 3. 3
Parses the line into an array of tokens using
.BR strtok (3),
splitting on spaces and newlines.
.IP 4. 3
Checks if the command is a built-in. If so, executes it internally.
.IP 5. 3
Searches each directory listed in the
.B PATH
environment variable for an executable matching the command name using
.BR access (2).
.IP 6. 3
If found, forks a child process using
.BR fork (2)
and executes the command with
.BR execve (2).
.IP 7. 3
If not found, prints an error message to stderr and continues.
.SH BUILTINS
The following built-in commands are supported:
.TP
.B exit [status]
Exit the shell. If a numeric
.I status
argument is provided, the shell exits with that value. Otherwise exits with 0.
.br
Usage: \fBexit\fR or \fBexit 42\fR
.TP
.B env
Print all current environment variables to standard output, one per line.
.br
Usage: \fBenv\fR
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Successful execution or exit without argument.
.TP
.B 1
A command was found but failed to execute.
.TP
.B 127
Command not found.
.TP
.I n
Exit status of the last command executed, or the value passed to
.BR exit .
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B PATH
A colon-separated list of directories in which the shell searches for
executable commands.
.SH ERRORS
If a command is not found, the shell prints the following to stderr:
.PP
.nf
prog_name: command_number: command: not found
.fi
.PP
If
.BR fork (2)
fails, the shell prints:
.PP
.nf
fork: error message
.fi
.PP
If
.BR execve (2)
fails, the shell prints:
.PP
.nf
execve: error message
.fi
.SH FILES
.TP
.B ./hsh
The shell executable.
